desc: Why are howler monkeys so loud? Their mating calls can be heard over three miles away. It’s all because they have a massively enlarged hyoid bone inside their throat. desc: Horse teeth are extremely long. How long are they? In this video, we find out while learning that horse teeth grow like push-up ice cream treats. The majority of a horse tooth is in reserve, hidden beneath their gum line. The tooth continuously erupts over the horse’s lifetime to replace the exposed tooth as it wears down. #animals #science #learnontiktok  Specimen use made possible by the University of Michigan Museum of Zoology

desc: What’s inside an antelope horn? In this video, we find out. We take a look inside a variety of animal horns and learn that a true animal horn is composed of a bony core and a keratin sheath. We look inside a bison horn, goat horn, antelope horn, and a kudu horn. In the wild, the keratin sheath is fused to the animal’s skull. #animals #science #learnontiktok  Specimen use made possible by the University of Michigan Museum of Zoology.

desc: How do flies bite? In this video we explore the answer. Biting flies have six “blades” on their faces. These are also called “stylets”. Each blade has a specific role in the biting process. #animals #science #learnontiktok

desc: Caterpillars have mostly fake legs - but where are they? At the front of their bodies they have 6 “true legs” and at the back they have 10 fake legs, also known as “prolegs”. #animals #science #learnontiktok

desc: Do starfish have eyes? How do starfish see? Turns out starfish do, in fact, have eyes. They have a single simple eye at the end of each arm. They use those eyes to look around underwater. #animals #science #learnontiktok
